#Introduction
Reinforcement learning (RL) has shown strong capabilities in learning complex decision-making behaviors through interaction with an environment. In particular, multi-agent reinforcement learning (MARL) introduces additional complexity, as multiple learning agents interact simultaneously, causing the environment to become non-stationary and highly dynamic.
This project explores emergent behavior in a continuous control adversarial MARL environment using two competing agents trained with Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO). One agent (Jeff) is trained to achieve a scoring objective, while the opposing agent (Tim) is trained to intercept and prevent success. Unlike discrete or turn-based environments, the continuous nature of the simulation allows for fine-grained movement strategies, leading to complex behavioral dynamics.
A key focus of this work is understanding how reward structure influences learned strategies. During training, we observe that agents do not simply learn to maximize the intended objective, but also exploit weaknesses in the reward design, resulting in unintended behaviors such as jittering, baiting, and inefficient movement patterns. These behaviors highlight the importance of careful reward shaping and environment design in multi-agent systems.
The project further investigates how modifications to reward functions and observation space affect agent behavior, stability, and strategy formation over iterative training cycles. The goal is not only to build a functional competitive system, but also to analyze and document the emergence of strategies under different learning conditions.
This project investigates the following question: how do reward structures, observation design, and self-play dynamics influence the emergence and stability of strategies in adversarial continuous-control multi-agent reinforcement learning systems?
